            "fillRule": "evenodd",
            "d": "M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"
          }}></path></svg></a>{`Why didn’t my alerts get grouped together?`}</h3>
    <p>{`There are three main reasons the Intelligent Alert Grouping algorithm did not group alerts that were on the same service:`}</p>
    <ol>
      <li parentName="ol">{`The alerts weren’t close together in time.`}</li>
      <li parentName="ol">{`The incoming alert data was not similar enough to desired alerts or was more similar to the alerts it was grouped with.`}</li>
      <li parentName="ol">{`Human response behavior via merging or moving alerts out of incidents overrode the desired behavior.`}</li>
    </ol>
    <p>{`The Intelligent Alert Grouping algorithm takes into consideration several different factors, which makes understanding why alerts are grouped or not difficult to trace. If you believe that there has been enough history for an alert to be grouped, but are still noticing some unexpected grouping behavior, please reach out to `}<a parentName="p" {...{
        "href": "mailto:support@pagerduty.com"
      }}>{`our Support team`}</a>{` and send links to specific incidents/alert groupings and summarize why the grouping behavior is unexpected.`}</p>
